1. The Core UI Backbone Rules
Grid Consistency (The 4px/8px Rule):

    Never use "random" spacing. Every margin, padding, and gap must be a multiple of 4px.

    Why: This keeps your pixel-art elements perfectly aligned and prevents that "sloppy" UI feel.

Visual Hierarchy via "Elevation":

    Use depth to differentiate components. Backgrounds should be flat, cards should have a subtle drop shadow (using your pixel-art palette), and active elements (like buttons) should have a slight "highlight" or border shift.

    Constraint: Never use more than 3 levels of "elevation" (e.g., Background -> Card -> Modal).

Action Affordance:

    Every interactive element must have a hover state. In a cozy pixel game, this is usually a 1-pixel border shift or a slight change in the background color brightness.

    Cursor Prompt: "For all buttons, implement a CSS :hover state that changes the border color to var(--color-accent) to signify interactability."

Resolution & Anti-Aliasing Lock:

    Every image asset MUST have image-rendering: pixelated;.

    Avoid any CSS properties that introduce blur (like box-shadow with large spreads or background-blur). Keep your shadows "hard" (spread: 0) to maintain the crisp pixel aesthetic.

2. Information Architecture: The "Cozy Layout"
To keep players relaxed, don't overwhelm them with menus. Follow these spatial rules:

    The "Rule of Corners": Place HUD elements in the corners (Moon balance top-right, Settings top-left). Leave the center of the screen as "breathing room" for the player’s room and avatar.

    Modal-First Design: If a feature isn't essential for exploration (like the Shop or Journaling), it should appear in a centered "Modal" window, not by changing the whole screen. This creates a psychological "pause" in the gameplay.

3. Maintaining Consistency (The "Fire and Forget" System)
To prevent "spaghetti UI" as you build, define these Atomic Components first. Tell Cursor:

    "Before building any pages, I need you to build a shared library of components: Button.tsx, Card.tsx, and Modal.tsx. Use these base components for every single screen in the app. Do not write custom CSS for layout containers; use these components."

